 the Lawyer as Social Architect, 1950– 1969 -- t14 Legal Teaching and the Reconceptualizing of the State: Global Law and New Legal Education Loci -- t15 Socratic Method, Philippine- style: To Unhave or Uphold? -- tPart 3 US Perspectives -- t16 Rethinking Assumptions about the Global Influence of US Legal Education -- t17 The Harvard Models in Their Native Habitat and Abroad: Reflections -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA critical history of the Americanization of legal education in fourteen countriesThe second half of the twentieth century witnessed the export of American power—both hard and soft—throughout the world. What role did US cultural and economic imperialism play in legal education? American Legal Education Abroad offers an unprecedented and surprising picture of the history of legal education in fourteen countries beyond the United States.Each study in this book represents a critical history of the Americanization of legal education, reexamining prevailing narratives of exportation, transplantation, and imperialism. Collectively, these studies challenge the conventional wisdom that American ideas and practices have dominated globally. Editors Susan Bartie and David Sandomierski and their contributors suggest that to understand legal education and to respond thoughtfully to the mounting present-day challenges, it is essential to look beyond a particular region and consider not only the ideas behind legal education but also the broader historical, political, and cultural factors that have shaped them.American Legal Education Abroad begins with an important foundational history by leading Harvard Law School historian Bruce Kimball, who explains the factors that created a transportable American legal model, and the book concludes with reflections from two prominent American law professors, Susan Carle and Bob Gordon, whose observations on recent disruptions within US law schools suggest that their influence within the global order of legal education may soon fall into further decline. This book should be considered an invaluable resource for anyone in the field of law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aLawxAmerican influences. 0aLawxStudy and teachingxAmerican influences. 0aLawxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 7aLAW / Legal Education.2bisacsh  aAnglo-American Legal Community.  aApprenticeship.  aAustralia.  aBrazil.  aCanada.  aCarnegie Foundation.  aCase Method.  aChina.  aCold War.  aDomestication.  aEngland.  aEstonia.  aFord Foundation.  aFrance.  aFunctionalism.  aGhana.  aGlobal Law.  aGlobalization.  aHarvard Law School.  aHarvard Model.  aInternationalization.  aIsrael.  aJapan.  aLangdell.  aLaw Reform.  aLaw Reviews.  aLaw and Society.  aLegal Culture.  aLegal Education.  aLegal Process School.  aLegal Process.  aLegal Structures.  aLegal Traditions.  aLegal Transplants.  aLon Fuller.  aNigeria.  aPhilippines.  aSocial Architects.  aSociology of Law.  aSocratic Method.  aStatehood.  aSweden.  aTransplants.  aUS.  aUnited States.1 aBadejogbin, Rebecca Emiene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartie, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartie, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarle, Susan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawuni, J. Jarpa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhirardi, José Garcez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGord